		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    A Primer on Being Noob: The First 5 Levels</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Threxx</a> | 
		            1/15/2001 2:30:48 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Welcome, young traveller!  Pull up a chair and have some ale.  You look weary.  Whats that you say?  You're new to these parts?  Nothing to be ashamed of, we were all new once... Eh?  Oh, you'er a =noob=.  No real idea of what this place is about?  Well, my friend, you have come to the right place.  I may not be an expert on every facet of Norrath, but I =am= a veteran here.  And I'll be more then happy to give you a few pointers that may not be so obvious from just reading the manual...<BR>
<BR>
Ok.  You have just finished character creation, and have appeared within the city of your choice, naked but for a hand weapon of some sort.  You'll want to check your Inventory right off the bat.  It should contain 5 bread cakes, 5 skins of milk, a red book, a rolled-up note, the weapon I mentioned earlier, and if you are a spellcaster, a pair of spell scrolls.  The very first thing you should do is drop or destroy your red book.  It's only use is to transform you into a Player-Killer, and there's 2 whole servers for the likes of thoes.  Secondly, scribe and memorize your spells, if you have any.  Lastly, arm yourself with your noob weapon.  It's not much, but it's all you have at the moment.<BR>
<BR>
That being done, you need to find your guild.  Depending on your race/class combo, this can be as easy as turning around, or as difficult as crossing a few maze-like city zones.  Recall that rolled-up note you have in your pocket?  Right-click on it.  Its your Guildnote, and it has valuable information for you, such as where your guildhouse is for your particular class, and/or who your Guildmaster is.  Find that worthy fellow, and hand him your note.  Tadaa!  You are now the proud owner of a Guild Tunic, a torn, filthy rag that bears some rough resembalance to a shirt.  It may be nasty, but it =will= provide you with some AC.  The exeption to this rule is Iksar, who recieve either a similar piece of armor, or a weapon, depending upon class.  Now, move about your guild, and talk to everyone there (talking to NPCs consists of targeting them, and hitting /h.  Simply say back to them what they say in brackets, with sutible additions to make it a sentance.  For example if an NPC says to you, &quot;will you do (this quest) for me?&quot;, just saying 'this quest' back will get you nowhere.  Saying 'Yes I will do this quest' will have a more favorable response).  Most of them will likely be merchants, but some of them will have quests for you to perform.  You can skip the quests for now.  I would like to note, however, that some quests give you a container of some sort, nessicary to compleate them.  ACCEPT THESE QUESTS.  You dont have to do them, but a container is probobly the single most valuable item a noob character can own.  As you may have noticed, your inventory is limited to 8 slots.  A good box or backpack can double that, meaning that you can stay in the field longer, and haul more loot to the merchants when you do return to town.  Just offhand, I can name 2 quests that give you a free container, the Fire Beetle Eye quest in Neriac 3rd Gate (talk to the fellow at the very top of the necromancer's guild, gets you a box), and the Curscale Armor quest in Cabilis (talk to the merchant across from the Court of Pain, gets you a backpack, and is the single best noob quest in game that I know of).  If you cannot find a 'quest' container, save your coppers to buy one.  I'd suggest any of the 'trade skill' kits (tailoring, fletching, ect), because not only do they tend to be light in weight, but they serve the dual purpose of carring loot =and= working as designed (just be sure not to hit 'combine' untill you are actually practicing your trade).  These do tend to be a bit pricy, however, so you might just want to stick to simple boxes and packs.   <BR>
<BR>
We'll pick out your stating skills at this point.  While chatting with the folks in your guild, you may have noticed that some of them were actually Trainers.  They offered you up a list of skills you could train in.  Now, most folks will advocate simply dumping all 5 of your initial points into your main weapon skill (be it 1-hand slash, 1-hand blunt, piercing, or hand-to-hand), and be done with it.  I beg to differ.  Drop 4 points into that weapon skill, but put your last point into Sense Heading.  Why sense heading?  Because its a heck of a lot easier to head northeast then it is to find loc +387.23 -4908.12 5.67.  Also because sense heading WILL NOT go up at an acceptable rate untill you have allocated at least one point to it.  Hotkey sense heading.  Use it constanly, even in combat.  It may be tedious, but it will pay off in the long run.  Im not saying that you should not learn how loc works.  I AM saying that for now, it's easier to use simple compass directions to get around.  <BR>
<BR>
Now that you have your guild tunic/weapon, and hopefully a bag or box of some kind, it's time to go make some XP.  Head outside your home city.  The area just outside the gates is what's commonly known as the 'newbie zone'.  Thats right, there's a zone made just for you  (Noteable exeptions to this rule are the newbie zone of Paineel, which is actually inside the city itself, and the newbie zone of Neriac, which is a goodly jog from the front gates).  Go forth and slay.  Its a good idea to Consider (right-click, or target and hit C) everything you see.  This is a fine habit to get into, as it's the only way to tell if you can beat a given beastie or not.  Cons go thusly: green (easy meat), blue (a bit of a fight, but you'll likely win), white (just as powerful as you are, it could go either way), yellow (real tough, dont tackle this alone), and red (just run, this will eat you for breakfast).  At first level, everything you see will con white or higher.  Well, no one ever said being a bold adventurer was going to be easy, did they?  Start killing.  Stick close to the guards, though.  Saving your young butt is what they do best.  You also might want to concider staying solo for your first few levels.  While the game is built around grouping, its wise to get a feel for your character, and what he's capeble of, before you throw your lot in with other brave adventurers. <BR>
<BR>
The first rule of combat is: DONT PANIC!  If you panic and try to run away blindly, you will only die tired and confused.  You may also die somewhere unfamilliar, which will mean your corpse may well decay (taking all your items with it) before you can find it again.  Stay aware of your surroundings, know where the guards are if things get too hairy and you have to break and run, and above all, keep cool.  Dying at levels 1-5 is actually a learning experiance, as you dont lose any hard-won XP from it.  True, it's a pain in the butt to have to recover your corpse (and re-memorize your spells, if you are a caster), but thoes are the breaks.  Note that at levels 1-5, you have only 20 minuits to CR (corpse-recover) before it rots.  After lvl 5 the time limit goes up significantly.<BR>
<BR>
The second rule of combat is: Loot your kills. This is how you make cash.  Its as easy as right-clicking on a carcass.  In fact, loot EVERY dead thing you see.  You would be surprised how many folks leave cold, hard cash just laying about on the ground.  Do not make the mistake of disdaining pennies, or base-level loot.  Copper adds up.  So do bat wings.  Also, many higher-level folks mave mastered the skill of Foraging, and may well drop foraged items on the ground.  Pick these up, too.  9 times out of 10 it'll be nothing but fishing grubs, but occasinaly you'll find foraged food or water that someone has discarded.  Some foraged items can even be sold to vendors for a few coin.<BR>
<BR>
Follow these basic steps, and you will be leveling, and building your bank account, in no time.  Before we wrap up, though, I'd like to make a few suggestions that have nothing to do with making XP or garnering choice loot.  The first one is be polite.  Dont rag on folks in /ooc or /shout, dont make fun of people's names or thier misfortunes.  Being rude only makes YOU look bad.  Belive me, folks will remember.  This goes for zonespam as well.  /shouting 'lvl 10 tank looking for group' 30 times a minuite is a stone garuntee that you will NOT get a group.  Secondly, use proper english.  Trollspeak or ikssar ssibilansse is terrific roleplay, and thats all well and good.  But k001-d00d-Sp33k is more then a little annoying.  Asking people, 'y r u nt Gr00pin wIt m3????' answers it's own question.  Save it for the chatrooms.  Lastly, play with honor.  Agree to share spawn points with other groups.  Give people the benifit of the doubt when, say, they train you.  It was most likely unintentinal.  Asking them if they are ok afterwards will make you look better then reflexivly flaming them in /ooc.  Might even make you a friend or 2.  Belive me, you yourself will start more then a few trains in your carrer.<BR>
<BR>
Thats about it.  Each class may have a slight variation to the theme, as well as each race, but these basic stratigies will be benificial to ANY starting character, regaurdless of race or class.  Good luck, and good hunting!<BR>
<BR>
Threxx<BR>
Iksar Warrior of the 37th season<BR>
Povar<BR>

